This collection explores judgement and how often we try to make sense of others at a surface level. snippet.textDisplay:
I don't want to reveal my name but I am 18 and as was diagnosed at 14 with Autism and here is my opinion on these questions;

I consider the word "special" Offensive - Somewhat agree - I feel as every one is special in some kind of way as we are all different independent people. Special is a word which means different things to people for me it means being unique and I don't want to be seen as unique because it reminds me I am different just because I have autism, I don't want to be different because we all deserve to be equal since we are all humans

I have trouble making friends - Agree - personally I have struggled making friends until I got to college because I found it difficult to communicate and didn't know how to act. I feel like I have to act different and hide the fact I have autism and because I choose to isolate my self a lot because I also have diagnosed anxiety and depression I've found it easier to be on my own so not got a chance to meet many people

Being diagnosed with autism helped understand me more - Agree - now at 17 I understand my triggers and what to avoid and this has helped me to become more confident and taught myself coping mechanisms

It bothers me when people pity me - Agree - when I tell someone new I have autism I get different responses but one time I have had a lady say "I'm sorry to hear that" Like I have been diagnosed something more severe. I already try hide my autism because I am ashamed to have it so I do not want pity

I would rather not have Autism - Somewhat agree - as I said before I try to hide my autism and not commonly use it in a conversation but I feel it defines me as a person and makes me who I am but on the other hand I feel my life could be easier if I didn't have it

I feel connected to other people on the spectrum - Strongly agree - Meeting some else on the spectrum makes me feel like we are already close as we have something in common and we can understand each other. I have been in learning difficulty youth groups where it really brought out my confidence because I know I wouldn't get judged and I had a close relationship to the people there

snippet.textDisplay: Interesting concept video.  Certainly worth doing.  For context, I am 52, so I grew up in a different world than these young people.  My late diagnosis was a year ago...yeah.  If we were still using the DSM-IV, I would be diagnosed as having Asperger's.  No support, no recognition, denial, I was just a bit "odd", "introverted", "awkward", "weird sensory issues", and my whole life was about..."Just deal with it" because you don't act anything at all like those poor little children.  Having the diagnosis and doing my research I am very happy with understanding why I am the way I am...and actually was a relief.  Having said that, the general public has almost no idea of what makes an autistic person autistic...I clearly didn't.  Even amongst pediatric health care workers, they often think of the small child with severe disabilities...not, for example, the brilliant pediatric cardiac surgeon with the private nurse at his/her side keeping their day straight.  There is a tendency for neurotypicals to have generalizations and stereotypes in their imagination for what an autistic person should act like...it's almost always wrong...and is why all the well-meaning, but ignorant, minimizing, and insulting comments we all receive.  More related to this video, Dr. Temple Grandin, put it best when describing "the spectrum" as more like a sound studio control board...the neurotypical with adjustments from say, "4-7"...the autistic with adjustments from "0-10"...pointing out that neurodiversity within the autistic community appears to be much broader than within the neurotypical community.  I believe most folks who have autism can recognize the nuanced behavior and communication of their autistic brothers and sisters, but beyond that, to say that we are all different would be an understatement.  Good video.  It needs to be seen more often....with the neurotypical community being the target audience.

I’m constantly having to mask, which is downright exhausting
There were rumours going around that someone in my class had autism (a kid overheard a teacher talking about me)

That was until someone found out and started gossiping about me.
She’s left the school now and I’ve decided to just be open about having autism but I’m still being gossiped about.

snippet.textDisplay: This Video Shows so many issues while Talking around the bush. The guy who says he makes Friends easily is one of those who talks to People as if they are his Friends and they laugh About him without him noticing because he doesnt feel the social cringe in the room. So even in his "own community" he is an outsider.I can also tell how he is used to People being all "oh and ah" About everything he says because he is used to getting all the Attention because he is "so strong and confident" even though he cant talk. Not even other autistic People. It's not "great" to be autistic because it makes life harder. And even though its a spectrum and some do better, there are those who will never even live close to a normal teenage and Young adult life because People will Always be nice and polity out of pity but never actually letting them participate in normal life. Rant over. :P

snippet.textDisplay:
Joseph really got to my heart. If not for AAC devices/software (what he’s using to speak), nonverbal kids’ developmental years would be unthinkably brutal on their self-confidence and socialization. Not to mention the sheer helplessness of being UNABLE to express FEELINGS or NEEDS!

I strongly believe my kid would not be verbal right now but for AAC devices. Please: If your little one is speech-delayed, seek testing and acquisition of a device like this for your child!! You can’t underestimate the positive impact these will make on their present and future!!

Thank you, Joseph, for sharing. 🙏 AND, thanks to this channel for creating & posting this!
Two words for the world: AWARENESS. ACCEPTANCE. ✌️

snippet.textDisplay:
I’ve noticed a lot of people assume autism means your slow or something
Most older people get it but when I was in highschool when they found out I had autism slot of them assumed I was slow
It’s always been a social thing for me like I can’t read facial expressions and don’t understand sarcasm very well and really don’t follow social norms
Most of my friends were either strange or hippies and one of the things I’ve learned after being around that type of person is that weird and strange people are the best and most interesting people to be around
Another thing is in middle school I always got called gay because of my weird body language and honestly it never bothered me that much cuz nobody took it seriously and after middle school I was never bullied because people aren’t as evil as many ppl think
Not everyone is good but most ppl will be friendly and excepting to you as long as your not being a dick
